oncepts are structured, how they are represented in the mind, and how they are expressed in language. Two introductory papers on concept types and frames set out the crucial role of attributes and frames for the representation of concepts. The topics of the contributions range from the interrelation between determination and reference of nominal expressions, the verbal and adjectival expression of attributes, and the analysis of metonymy to the frame-based representation of action-related concepts and the classification of mental disorders in psychiatry. The collection of articles provided by this volume will be of interest to researchers and advanced students in the fields of semantics, pragmatics, philosophy of mind, and the cognitive sciences.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access under a CC BY-NC-ND 4.0 license: uhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-nd/4.0 uhttps://www.degruyter.com/dg/page/open-access-policy  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 25. Feb 2021) 4aCognitive Frames. 4aConcept Types. 4aDetermination. 4aSemantic Fields. 7aLANGUAGE ARTS & DISCIPLINES / General.2bisacsh  aAction-Frames.  aAlexander Tokar.  aAlexander Ziem.  aAssociative Anaphora.  aBarsalou Frames.  aBrigitte Schwarze.  aChristian Horn.  aCognitive Frames.  aCognitive Linguistic.  aConcept Frames.  aConcept Types.  aConcept of FEAR.  aDefiniteness Effect.  aDetermination.  aDiachrony.  aExperimental Method.  aFrame Theory.  aFrameNet.  aFrench.  aFunctional Concepts.  aFunctional Frames.  aGerhard Schurz.  aGottfried Vosgerau.  aHana Filip.  aHans Geisler.  aHeinrich-Heine-Universität Düsseldorf.  aIrem Girgin.  aIrene Russo.  aItalian Nouns.  aJulia Weiland.  aJürgen Zielasek.  aKarin Fauerbach.  aLaura Kallmeyer.  aLiane Ströbel.  aLinguistic Realizations.  aManner